Issue faces:
1.
After completing the initial phase of the project, while testing the APIs, the /api/users endpoint returned
a 500 Internal Server Error, even though other endpoints like /api/bookings and /api/packages were working correctly.
I carefully rechecked the entire project code, but everything appeared correct, and the issue still persisted.
To investigate further, I examined the database to verify whether all tables were created as expected. I discovered
that the User table had not been created at all, while the booking and travelpackage tables were successfully created.
After researching the issue, I identified that user is a reserved keyword in PostgreSQL, which caused the table creation
to fail. I resolved the problem by explicitly renaming the table using the @Table(name = "users") annotation in the User
entity. This experience helped me understand the importance of avoiding reserved keywords and properly configuring ORM
mappings in database-driven applications.












# docker container setup for setting up postgres DB for the project:
docker run --name postgresDB \
-e POSTGRES_USER=bhavdip \
-e POSTGRES_PASSWORD=bhavdip123 \
-e POSTGRES_DB=travelease \
-p 5432:5432 \
-v postgres-data:/var/lib/postgresql \
-d postgres


# to connect to the database created, in the terminal:
docker exec -it postgresDB psql -U bhavdip -d travelease
(after this we will be inside the database, and can run sql queries)
